quest_title: A long solenoid has 2000 turns wound over a length of 0.30 m. The area of its cross-section is 1.2 \(\times\) 10\({}^{-3}\) m\({}^{2}\). Around its central section a coil of 300 turns is wound. If an initial current of 2 A in the solenoid is reversed in 0.25 sec, the e.m.f. induced in the coil is equal to
explanation_txt:
Mutual inductance is given by
\(M=\cfrac{\mu_{0} N_{p} N_{\mathrm{s}} A_{2}}{l}\)
\(\text { and } E=M \cfrac{d i}{d t} \)
\(M=\cfrac{4 \pi \times 10^{-7} \times 2000 \times 300 \times 1.2 \times 10^{-3}}{0.30} \)
\(M=96 \pi \times 10^{-5} \)
\(E=M \cfrac{d i}{d t}=96 \pi \times 10^{-5} \times \cfrac{4}{0.25} \)
\(E=M \cfrac{d i}{d t}=4.8 \times 10^{-2} \mathrm{volt.} \)

quest_title: A what speed should a source of sound moves so that the observer finds the apparent frequency equal to half of original frequency.
explanation_txt:
Since apparent frequency decreases hence source must be moving away from observer, apparent frequency is given by :

\(f^{\prime}=\left(\cfrac{v}{v+v_{s}}\right) \times f\)

\(\begin{aligned} \Rightarrow \quad \mathrm{f} / 2 &=\left(\cfrac{v}{v+v_{s}}\right) \times \mathrm{f} \Rightarrow \mathrm{v}+\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{s}}=2 \mathrm{v} \\ & \therefore \mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{s}}=\mathrm{v} \end{aligned}\)

quest_title: Which of the following should be done in order to prepare 0.40M -NaCl starting with 100ml of 0.30M NaCl? (Mol.wt. of NaCl = 58.5)
explanation_txt:
The given solution is of concentration 0.3M so to increase the concentration one has to either evaporate the excess water or add an extra amount of NaCl to the solution.

Amount of NaCl to be added = 100 ml of 0.1N NaCl = 0.1*0.1 gram equivalent = 0.01 gram equivalent = 0.01 moles

Amount of water to be evaporated can be calculated as

100 ml of 0.3 N NaCl = 75 ml of 0.4N NaCl

\(\therefore\) Either 0.01 moles of NaCl should be added or 25 ml of water should be evaporated.

quest_title: Which of the following electronic configurations would you expect to have the lowest ionization energy?
explanation_txt:
Ionization energy is the minimum amount of energy required to remove the most loosely bound electron, the valence electron, of an isolated neutral gaseous atom or molecule.

Alkali metals (\(\text{1s\(^{2}\)}\) \(\text{2s\(^{2}\)}\) \(\text{2p\(^{6}\)}\) \(\text{3s\(^{1}\)}\))(Na) have low ionization energy because of their low effective nuclear charge and the ability to attain a noble gas configuration by losing just one electron.

quest_title: If \( A, B , C \) are matrices of order \( 3 \times 3, 3 \times 2 \) and \(3 \times 2\) respectively, which of the following is not defined?
explanation_txt:
Note that if \( X \) is of order \( m \times n \) and \(Y\) is of order \( n \times p \), the order of \( XY \) is \( m \times p \).

Since \(A\) is of order \( 3 \times 3 \) and \(B\) is of order \(3 \times 2\), \(AB\) is of order \(3 \times 2\) equal to order of \(C\). So, (a) is defined.

Since \(B\) and \(C\) are of order \( 3 \times 2 \), \( BC^{T} \) and \(CB^{T}\) are of order \(3 \times 3 \).Also, since \( A \) is of order \( 3 \times 3 \), \(A^2\) is also of order \(3 \times 3\)

Hence, \( BC^{T} - A^2 \) is defined and is of order \(3 \times 3 \). So, (b) is also defined.

By similar explanation, (c) is also defined.

But since \(BC \) is not defined, (d) is not defined.

\(\tan \theta=\cfrac{\mathrm{u}_{y}}{\mathrm{u}_{x}}=\cfrac{17.5}{20}\)

\(\therefore \theta=\tan ^{-1}\left(\cfrac{17.5}{20}\right)=41.2^{\circ}\)

\(R=u_{x} \cdot \cfrac{2 u_{y}}{g}=\cfrac{20 \times 2 \times 17.5}{10}=70 \mathrm{m}\)
